            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Marco Vitali is a product of old San Francisco, born and raised in the heart of North Beach. His grandparents, immigrants from Lucca, established a beloved neighborhood deli, a place redolent with the scent of cured meats and fresh focaccia that defined Marco\u2019s childhood. He grew up stocking shelves and working the counter, learning the rhythms of a small family business and the value of a hard day's work. It was assumed he would one day take over.\n\nHowever, after earning his Associate's degree in Business Administration from City College, Marco made a difficult choice. Watching his parents struggle against rising rents and changing tastes, he sought a more stable path. This was his first major turning point: choosing security over tradition. He leveraged his practical skills and no-nonsense work ethic, landing an entry-level administrative job. Over two decades, he steadily climbed the ladder, proving his talent for streamlining systems and managing people. Today, he\u2019s a respected Operations Manager for a boutique market research firm south of Market.\n\nMarco\u2019s life is one of deliberate routine and quiet satisfaction. He still lives in North Beach, in a rent-controlled apartment he\u2019s had for fifteen years, a rare anchor in the turbulent city. His 1.5-mile walk to the office is a cherished daily ritual, a time to observe the architectural details and the shifting morning light. A long-term relationship ended amicably five years ago, and while he\u2019s open to connection, he is content with his small, tight-knit circle of friends and regular Sunday dinners with his sister.\n\nHe feels a deep, sometimes melancholic, connection to a San Francisco that is rapidly fading. He laments the loss of old businesses but appreciates the city's dynamism. His dream isn\u2019t one of grand ambition but of refined passion: he fantasizes about saving enough to travel through Italy for six months, reconnecting with his roots. He aspires to a future defined not by wealth, but by stability, meaningful connection, and the perfect espresso from the cafe on his corner, where the barista knows his name."
        },
